title Waymark hash corrected to SHA3-512; the drawn word changes from FITS to HAWM
prompt Keaton asked to make sure the hashing we just worked on (the waymark derivation resolving the Genode/GrapheneOS G0 naming collision) uses SHA3.
think Checked rather than assumed there was a real gap: tools/waymark_derive.rish (written the prior turn) shelled out to plain sha256sum -- SHA-2, not SHA-3, despite the similar name -- while this tree already carries a ratified, specific policy for exactly this (context/specs/20260703-191112_resins-and-hash-tiers.md): a two-tier SHA3 family, `openssl dgst -sha3-256`/`-sha3-512` as the named host oracle, chosen by the promise the name makes rather than by habit. Confirmed openssl on this host actually supports sha3-224/256/384/512 before touching anything, and cross-checked the resins policy's own worked example (SHA3-256("test")) against a known test vector to trust the tool.
think Chose SHA3-512 over SHA3-256 by reading the policy's own tier table rather than defaulting to whichever tier I'd already used elsewhere: Canonical/SHA3-512 is named for things that "must mean one thing for as long as the work endures," with "Aurora stage names" listed as an example -- a ladder's own permanent waymark is exactly that kind of naming-grade identity, not a high-volume working-store unit (the SHA3-256 tier's own examples: Amber resins, Tablecloth blobs).
think Recomputed by hand first (raw shell) before touching the script, to know what to expect: input "grapheneos-pixel-mobile-emulation" -> SHA3-512 first-8-hex 854b9a74 -> decimal 2236324468 -> index 2003 of 5526 -> HAWM. Then edited tools/waymark_derive.rish's one hashing line (sha256sum -> openssl dgst -sha3-512 | awk '{print $NF}' | cut -c1-8, parsing openssl's own "SHA3-512(stdin)= <hex>" line shape) and reran the actual witness -- GREEN, matching the hand computation exactly.
think Propagated the new word everywhere the old one had already spread this same day: the spec doc's own algorithm description and worked example, context/LEXICON.md's Waymark entry, the G-ladder's living twin (rung table, stamp line, Related section), and the ROADMAP.md/TASKS.md bullets recording today's align pass -- five files, all still "living" as of this same session, none yet closed into a dated historical record.
think Deliberately did not edit the prior turn's own session log (20260716-115927) or its session-logs/README.md index row -- accrete-never-break: that log honestly recorded what happened at that moment (sha256sum, FITS), and rewriting it would erase the real mistake rather than let this new log name the correction plainly, the same discipline this tree already applies to tip-to-nib.
think Added a "named correction, honestly kept" paragraph directly into the spec doc itself, not only into session-logs, so a future reader who only opens the living spec (never the dated log) still learns FITS was a real, wrong, superseded first draft rather than silently seeing HAWM with no trace of the miss.
obs The actual index-and-lookup logic (corpus extraction, modulo, exclude-check) needed zero changes -- only the one hashing line and its label. A one-line mistake, caught within the same working session, cost five files' worth of propagation to fix cleanly; naming schemes are exactly the kind of thing worth getting right before more references accrete on top of a wrong word.
file tools/waymark_derive.rish -- hashing line swapped sha256sum -> openssl dgst -sha3-512; header comment cites the resins-and-hash-tiers policy and names the tier choice; rerun GREEN with the new word
file context/specs/20260716-115927_waymark-ladder-naming-and-g0-collision-fix.md -- algorithm step 2 now names SHA3-512 and the resins-and-hash-tiers citation; worked example and rung table updated to HAWM0-HAWM3; new "named correction, honestly kept" paragraph; Version line gains a corrected-124840 clause
file context/LEXICON.md -- Waymark entry names SHA3-512 and the hash-tiers citation; example updated to HAWM0
file context/specs/two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md -- stamp line, rung table (HAWM0-HAWM3), and honest-register paragraph updated; also recorded Keaton's own KVM-policy word (host-terminal one-shot) at HAWM0, named as policy-decided but not yet built
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- three bullets' FITS mentions corrected to HAWM, including the top mega-line's own continued-115927 clause, which also now names the KVM policy as decided rather than still-open
file work-in-progress/ROADMAP.md -- the 115927 align-pass paragraph's FITS mentions corrected to HAWM
recommend keep-going -- the naming fix is now internally consistent and witnessed correctly; the next real work is the HAWM0 implementation itself (Android SDK install, AVD, a host-terminal launch script mirroring tools/lane_kvm_onpath_host.rish), already policy-cleared by Keaton's own word and not blocked on anything from this correction.
